=============================================================================
1. FEATURES OVERVIEW
=============================================================================

  +-----------------------------+--------------------------------------------+
  | Feature                     | Description                                |
  +-----------------------------+--------------------------------------------+
  | Directory tree rendering    | Visual representation of file hierarchy    |
  | File content capture        | Reads text content of files (up to a       |
  |                             | configurable size limit)                   |
  | SHA256 hashing              | Computes SHA-256 hash of every file        |
  | Dual output format          | JSON (structured) or Markdown (human)      |
  | Ignore rules                | Respects .gitignore, .snapcatignore, and   |
  |                             | custom ignore files                        |
  | Configurable                | CLI flags, .snapcatconfig file, or         |
  |                             | SNAPCAT_* environment variables            |
  | Parallel processing         | Uses Rayon for fast multi-threaded file    |
  |                             | reading                                    |
  | Verbose logging             | Built-in tracing for debugging             |
  | Rich error diagnostics      | Powered by miette for user-friendly errors |
  | Library + binary            | Use as a standalone CLI or integrate the   |
  |                             | library into your own Rust project         |
  +-----------------------------+--------------------------------------------+


=============================================================================
2. INSTALLATION
=============================================================================

Snapcat is not yet published on crates.io.  You can build from source or use
a pre-compiled binary from the GitHub Releases page.

2.1 Pre-built binary

  Download the appropriate archive for your platform from the Releases page
  and extract it.  On Linux (x86_64):

    curl -LO https://github.com/mroczect/snapcat/releases/download/cli-v0.1.0/snapcat-x86_64-linux.tar.gz
    tar -xzf snapcat-x86_64-linux.tar.gz
    sudo install -m 755 snapcat /usr/local/bin/
    snapcat --help

  macOS (Intel or Apple Silicon) archives are also provided.

2.2 Build from source

  Requirements: Rust (edition 2024 or later), Git.

    git clone https://github.com/mroczect/snapcat.git
    cd snapcat
    cargo build --release
    ./target/release/snapcat --help

2.3 Install via cargo 

    cargo install --git https://github.com/mroczect/snapcat.git


=============================================================================
3. QUICK START
=============================================================================

  Run Snapcat against the current directory with default settings:

    snapcat

  This prints a JSON document containing the directory tree and the content +
  SHA256 of every file (respecting .gitignore).  To save the result to a file:

    snapcat -o snapshot.json

  For a human-readable Markdown report:

    snapcat -f markdown -o report.md


=============================================================================
4. COMMAND-LINE USAGE
=============================================================================

  snapcat [OPTIONS] [PATH]

  PATH                  Target directory (default: current directory).

  Options:
    -f, --format <FMT>  Output format: json or markdown (default: json)
    -o, --output <FILE> Write output to FILE instead of stdout
    -v, --verbose       Enable verbose (trace) logging
    --max-depth <N>     Maximum directory depth (0 = unlimited)
    --include-hidden    Include hidden files and directories
    --follow-symlinks   Follow symbolic links (may loop)
    -j, --jobs <N>      Number of parallel threads (default: number of CPUs)
    --max-file-size <N> Maximum file size in bytes to read (default: 10 MB)

  Examples:

    snapcat -f markdown -o full.md
    snapcat --max-depth 3 --include-hidden
    snapcat -j 4 --max-file-size 5242880   # 5 MB


=============================================================================
5. CONFIGURATION
=============================================================================

Snapcat can be configured via a file, environment variables, and CLI flags.
CLI flags take highest precedence, then environment variables, then the
config file.

5.1 Configuration file: .snapcatconfig

  Place a file named .snapcatconfig in the current directory (or home
  directory, etc., depending on the `config` crate search path).  It can
  contain any of the following keys:

    format: "json" | "markdown"
    output: "/path/to/output"
    max_depth: 5
    include_hidden: true | false
    follow_symlinks: true | false
    ignore_files: [".snapcatignore", ".myignore"]
    max_file_size: 10000000
    verbose: true | false
    jobs: 4

  If the file is absent, sensible defaults are used.

5.2 Environment variables

  Prefix SNAPCAT__ and use double underscores as separators:

    SNAPCAT__FORMAT=markdown
    SNAPCAT__OUTPUT=/tmp/snap.md
    SNAPCAT__MAX_DEPTH=3
    SNAPCAT__INCLUDE_HIDDEN=true

  Note: SNAPCAT__INCLUDE_HIDDEN=true sets include_hidden to true, etc.


=============================================================================
6. OUTPUT FORMATS
=============================================================================

6.1 JSON

  A pretty-printed JSON object with two keys:

    {
      "tree": "project/\n├── src/\n│   ├── main.rs\n│   └── lib.rs\n...",
      "files": [
        {
          "path": "src/main.rs",
          "content": "fn main() { ... }",
          "sha256": "e3b0c442..."
        }
      ]
    }

  The "tree" field contains a rendered directory tree (same style as the
  Unix `tree` command).  The "files" array contains an entry for every
  regular file that was successfully read.

6.2 Markdown

  A human-readable document:

    # Snapcat Output

    ```
    project/
    ├── src/
    │   ├── main.rs
    │   └── lib.rs
    ```

    ## Files

    ### src/main.rs
    ```
    fn main() { ... }
    ```
    SHA256: `e3b0c442...`

  Each file gets its own section with the content in a code block and the
  SHA256 hash printed below.


=============================================================================
7. LIBRARY USAGE (Rust)
=============================================================================

Add Snapcat as a dependency in your Cargo.toml:

  [dependencies]
  snapcat = { git = "https://github.com/mroczect/snapcat.git" }

Then use the library in your code:

  use snapcat::handler::config::{SnapConfig, OutputFormat};
  use snapcat::{snap, output};

  let config = SnapConfig::default();
  let result = snap(Path::new("./my_project"), &config)?;
  output(result, &config)?;

See the source documentation for more details.


=============================================================================
8. ERROR HANDLING
=============================================================================

Snapcat uses `miette` for rich error reporting.  Common errors include:

  - DirectoryNotFound       – the given path does not exist or is not a
                              directory.
  - FileReadError           – a file could not be read (permissions, etc.).
  - FileTooLarge            – a file exceeded max_file_size.
  - ConfigLoadError         – .snapcatconfig could not be parsed.
  - InvalidConfig           – a configuration value is invalid.
  - OutputCreateError       – the output file could not be written.

All errors include a diagnostic code (e.g., snapcat::io::read) and, where
possible, a helpful suggestion.


=============================================================================
9. EXAMPLES
=============================================================================

  - Generate a full JSON snapshot of a Rust project, excluding hidden files:

      snapcat -o project.json

  - Create a Markdown document that you can feed to an LLM:

      snapcat -f markdown --max-file-size 1048576 -o context.md

  - Restrict depth to 2 and ignore any .snapcatignore file:

      snapcat --max-depth 2 --ignore-files ""


